[[File:OldsmobileOmegaES2800.jpg|thumb|left|1981 Oldsmobile Omega ES 2800 performance variant]]
<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:1981SportOmega.jpg|thumb|left|1981 Oldsmobile SportsOmega]] -->
[[File:Oldsmobile Omega coupe.jpg|thumb|left|1983 Oldsmobile Omega coupe]]

The X-bodies were all-new front-wheel drive cars for 1980. Engine choices were limited to Pontiac's [[GM Iron Duke engine|Iron Duke]] [[inline-four engine]] and the new corporate 2.8&nbsp;L [[GM 60-Degree V6 engine#LE2|LE2]] [[V6]] designed specifically for this platform. Transmissions were the 4 speed manual or the TH125 3-speed automatic.

Unlike the [[Chevrolet Citation]], which the car was based upon, the Omega range consisted of only a 2-door coupe and 4-door sedan, with upright styling and a distinctive split grille.

Aside from the standard and Brougham models produced in all five years, sportier models were also built.  These included the SX coupe (replaced by the ES in 1982), ES sedan, and pioneering urethane plastic-fendered 1981 SportOmega, which came with wild red-and-orange striping, white-over-gray paint, and a sloping front grille assembly shared with the SX and ES. Notably, the sportier models were available with both the L4 and V6 engines.<ref>1981 and 1983 Sales Brochures</ref>

Beginning in 1982, the Chevrolet high-output (130 horsepower) 2.8L V6 became available on ES models. In 1983, the ES was only available in the sedan body style.

The X-body Omega, like its sister vehicles (the [[Chevrolet Citation]], [[Pontiac Phoenix]] and [[Buick Skylark]]), proved fairly trouble-prone early on, necessitating an astounding number of government-mandated [[Product recall|recall]]s for [[GM X platform (1980)#Mechanical problems|braking problems]], fluid leaks and suspension issues.  While Omega was the only one of the four X-cars to sell better in 1981 than in 1980 (147,918 versus 134,323), starting in 1982, production fell dramatically.  Only 77,469 Omegas were built in '82, with 53,926 in 1983 and 52,986 in swan-song 1984.

For 1985, the Omega was replaced by the [[GM N platform|N-body]] [[Oldsmobile Cutlass Calais|Calais]].
